Do you have a black box in your car?
While U.S. road designers are trying to find money to repair a dismantling highway system, many begin to see the solution in a small black box neatly mounted on the dashboard of your car.
These devices, which track every mile driven by a motorist and pass this information on to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt to modernize America’s outdated highway financing system undertaken by the planned authorities of Washington and the state.
Usually, the boring arena of highway planning unexpectedly sparked intense debates and colorful alliances.
The libertarians joined the environmental groups in lobbying for the government’s right to use small boxes to track the number of miles you travel and perhaps even where you travel them – and then use that information when creating tax accounts.
