However, House of Representatives member Bill Shuster (Republican, Pennsylvania), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also viewed the system as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free-market advocates at the Reason Foundation are also thrilled that they will make drivers pay for every mile.
“It’s not just a tax that will go into the black hole,” said Adrian Moore, Vice President of Political Affairs, Reason.
People are paying directly for what they get.
The move is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers, who in 2011 called on Congress to move towards mispayment.
The U.S. Senate approved last year a $90 million pilot project that would involve around 10,000 cars.
