Goldman Sachs warns of risks to Russian economy
Goldman Sachs warned of the growing risks to the main driver of fragile economic growth in Russia - consumption.
This is primarily the crisis of non-payments on unsecured consumer loans and mass reductions in workers.
Our main concern right now is not that growth has slowed down, but rather the structure of that growth.
Lately, it is entirely due to consumption, which will almost not reduce turnover," said Goldman Sachs chief economist Clemens Grafe, presenting yesterday's quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy.
The nominal wage growth in Russia is now about 10%.
With inflation at 6%, it will be able to provide future consumer demand at around the current level, Goldman Sachs expects.
But the profitability of Russian companies is declining, so they are likely to optimise personnel costs.
Today we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages grow by 10%, then GDP - by only 2%, - Mr. Grafe explained.
The companies are facing a reduction in profitability.
If it does not grow, it can lead to layoffs and unemployment growth.
Russian business can not raise salaries, says chief economist Barclays Capital on Russia and the CIS Vladimir Pantyushin.
Unemployment near historical lows, competition for workers is high.
In order to lure employees from the side or keep current ones, employers have to raise wages.
Consumption in Russia support is alive and very fast growth in consumer lending.
According to Mr. Graf, because of the extremely high rates on consumer loans, this type of lending does not have a multiplier effect on the economy of the country.
“We have not seen any benefits for the economy from the growth of consumer lending, money does not diverge across the economy, but returns to the same banks in the form of interest payments,” the economist said.
But the problem is another - Goldman Sachs expects a growth in the delay on unsecured loans.
They are mostly taken by the poor, who have nothing to provide for.
Interest rates on such loans are high.
As a result, they are often not returned," said Mr. Grafe.
Therefore, the second threat to the growth of the economy in Russia is a possible crisis of non-payments on unsecured loans.
Vasily Solodkov, director of the BSE Banking Institute, is already seeing signs of a growing banking crisis.
Small credit organizations, not having access to cheap resources such as the state banks, were forced to attract the funds of the population at high rates.
In response, the state banks went on the path of war and began to reduce credit rates, - continues the economist.
Small credit institutions cannot issue loans at the same rates, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If the state banks do not give up dumping, Russia is in danger of a full-fledged banking crisis, believes Vasily Solodkov.
The deprivation of licenses of a number of banks in recent weeks, the economist considers a forerunner of a mass collapse.
“The state banks themselves will not be able to cope with this situation: the deposit insurance system was not originally designed for a systemic crisis,” warns the head of the institute.
But the growth of consumption will slow and without a crisis of non-payments, the investment bank believes, - due to the refusal to index the salaries of civil servants and military, laid down in the current version of the draft budget.
In part, the impact on consumption will be mitigated by freezing tariffs on natural monopolies (and, as a result, a decrease in inflation).
But only partially: if the investment does not grow (and there is no prerequisite for this yet - see the reference), consumption growth will still slow down, Goldman Sachs is confident.
Vladimir Pantyushin of Barclays Capital does not yet see the prerequisites for implementing pessimistic scenarios.
“The main risk is still falling oil prices,” he said.
According to him, Russia’s economy will begin to decline at oil prices below $90/bar.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the central bank is not yet in a position to reduce interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical picture: inflation has fallen and banks have started to raise rates.
This may mean that they didn’t believe the central bank that announced the transition to targeting inflation,” Clemens Grafe said.
The Central Bank’s interest rate policy on market rates does not affect, it only affects interbank lending rates.
“For the Central Bank, this is a breakdown of all hopes,” Clemens Grafe said.
The money received at the Central Bank’s auctions is not used by banks to lend the economy, but to manage their liquidity.
As soon as the rate decreases, the exchange rate immediately changes, this means that the funds are trying to escape speculation against the ruble.
“Sooner or later, the Central Bank will understand that this strategy is not working,” Grafe said, recalling that the state plans to let the ruble into “free swimming” by the end of 2015.
But it will have to do so sooner or raise the central bank’s key rate (5.5%), he believes.
According to his estimation, the rate of the ruble is now artificially exceeded by 10%.
The ruble only one way - to weaken, - concludes the expert.
But if the central bank falls into the financiers at least a shadow of doubt that the liquidation of the currency corridor is not part of the policy of weakening the ruble, it can crush the ruble much more strongly.
