The speech gene proved to be a stimulator of synapses formation
Scientists at Johns Hopkins University and the Mount Sinai Medical School have discovered a protein that allows Foxp2 to perform its function by stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in Science, on the website of the journal you can read its short content.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known gene whose function is directly related to speech.
Its role was established in 2001 thanks to the discovery of a family of several people who could not pronounce words correctly and sometimes did not even understand each other.
The researchers found that members of the family had disrupted the work of the Foxp2 gene, but how it performs its function remained unknown.
In a new study, biologists have shown that at least part of its functions Foxp2 performs as a stimulant for the formation of new synapses in the brain area associated with speech formation.
This is done through another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was discovered as a result of the search for factors that stimulate the formation of synapses.
SRPX2 has been one of 10 similar genes found by the authors, with only Foxp2 vying for its activity.
The fact that SRPX2 really affects vocalization, the scientists confirmed in an experiment on mice.
When the animals were artificially reduced in gene activity, they cried less when separated from the mother.
If the activity of the gene was restored, the frequency of the sounds emitted was also restored.
Previously, the mice were also shown to be associated with the vocalization of Foxp2 itself.
Animals that were given a human copy of the gene ate more actively and at a lower frequency than normal mice.
To date, however, scientists do not know whether Foxp2’s work and, accordingly, its managed SRPX2 are linked to purely “mechanical” sound-forming properties or thinner processes.
