According to the Levada Center, 40% of citizens to varying degrees approve of the holding of "Russian marches": of these, 11% are definitely positive and 29% - "rather positive".
The popularity of the idea of "Russian marches" is gradually growing - in 2006, these actions were welcomed by only 14% of Russians, and in December 2010, the holding of such events was already supported by double the number of citizens (28%).
“Definitely negative” to “Russian marches” are only 7% of Russians, “rather negative” – 19%.
A further 35% were unable to formulate their attitude to this stock.
This year, the mayor of Moscow agreed to hold a "Russian March" of up to 15,000 people in Lublin, the head of the security department of the capital, Alexei Majorov, said today.
This campaign of nationalists has been held every year on the Day of National Unity since 2005.
On the question of sociologists “Did you hear about the “Russian marches” being held in Russia on November 4 under slogans of protection of Russian rights in Russia?” three-quarters (75%) of citizens answered negative.
Currently, only one in five Russians (20%) know about this stock.
It is noteworthy that in December 2010, almost a third of citizens (31%) heard about "Russian marches".
Recall that three years ago on December 11 in Manezhnaya Square there was a natural rally of nationalists, which turned into mass unrest.
“Levada Center” also asked the Russians about what holiday is celebrated on November 4.
In two years, the number of people who know the right answer (People’s Unity Day) has increased from 41% to 49%.
However, only 15% of citizens are going to celebrate this holiday.
Approximately as many (17%) intend to celebrate the 7th of November Day of the October Revolution.
Most citizens (62%) are not going to celebrate any of these holidays.
