On the Day of National Unity in 2012, the nationalists marched from the Yakimanska promenade to the Artist’s Central House, where the rally took place.
The organizers estimated the number of participants at 20,000 people, the Ministry of Interior called the figure 6,000.
Report: Obama’s Electoral Headquarters Considered Biden’s Exemption in favour of Hillary Clinton
According to The New York Times, President Barack Obama’s closest advisers secretly considered replacing Vice President Joe Biden with Hillary Clinton’s 2012 nomination in the ballot box.
This discovery is the brightest sensation from all-expected book by Mark Galperin and John Hailemann about the 2012 campaign "Bets Doubled: The Game Changed 2012".
The Times received a copy of the forthcoming book and reported on Thursday evening that the president’s closest aides had conducted “scale studies in focus groups and public opinion polls at the end of 2011” to assess whether Biden’s exception could help.
According to The Times political critic Jonathan Martin, the book gives a detailed description of the attempts of high-ranking election officials and the White House, namely the former head of the White House administration, Bill Daley, to assess the effect of the Gothenburg administration.
The possible replacement was a secret, carefully guarded in the Chicago election headquarters and in the Oval Office.
Only six of the president’s closest advisers — including Daley, former head of Obama’s election headquarters Jim Messin and former White House senior advisers David Axelrod and David Pluff — knew the replacement was under consideration.
The book "Double Bets" claims that Daley was the initiator of an attempt to replace Biden despite their "close personal relationship", but ultimately gave up this step when their data was better shown that Clinton's addition to the "non-election list."
In an interview with Martin Daley, he confirmed that the administration was indeed considering replacing Biden Clinton.
“I was actively in favor of considering a lot of things, and that was one of them,” Daley told the paper.
You have to remember that the president was in terrible shape at the time, so we thought, “Oh my God, what should we do?”
Although Daley described the study as a “necessary check,” Martin told CNN representative Anderson Cooper that the election headquarters had invested quite a bit in the study of whether this step would bring dividends to the vote.
“Election staff don’t spend such amounts of money on polls and focus groups unless they take something seriously,” Martin said in the AK 360 program.
It is unclear, however, whether Obama knew that his team was studying the possibility of a replacement.
Martin told CNN that he had asked Daley if his then boss knew about a possible move.
Although Daley said he did not think the president “was aware” of a possible replacement, the former head of the administration admitted that “maybe” Obama knew.
Martin added that “Double stakes” does not provide a clear answer to the question of whether the results of the political probe reached the Obama desk.
Cooper asked Martin if he was serious about Obama’s lack of knowledge about the possibility of banning Biden from the electoral roll.
“Maybe,” Martin replied.
