Premature puberty: aging earlier
African-American and Latino-American girls tend to reach sexual maturity earlier than their white peers, studies show.
Physical changes do not mean that sexual maturation is close
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are to blame.
Experts believe that the obesity epidemic may be one of the launch mechanisms of early puberty
The tendency to early puberty is not so pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etherige is a journalist who specializes in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be afraid if her daughter begins to form the conceptions of the mammary gland and grows the frontal hair at 7 or 8 years?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplovitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent the norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring my parents — usually that doesn’t mean a rapid onset of full sexual maturity,” Kaplovitz said.
Evident signs of development, such as growing breasts, forehead and armpit hair and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a small shift in the age of menarche (the first menstruation) over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, down from 12.75 in 1970.
“After the breast begins to develop, it takes at least two or three years before the menarche,” said Kaplovitz, who is also the author of the book Early Puberty in Girls: How to Cope with This Common Problem.
Time is the most accurate test of how sexual maturation will progress.
There is discussion about what constitutes the actual onset of sexual maturity, but it is considered “premature” when breast enlargement is accompanied by a sharp increase in growth up to 8 years.
In most cases, the process will slow down or stop – this is something that the pediatrician can follow closely.
Faster progression can serve as a basis for tests by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are procedures to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to slowing growth and low growth in adulthood.
Recommendations for medication or hormone therapy are based on the child’s age, level of development, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplovitz is wary of the drugs, but admits that “the suppression of sexual maturation can alleviate the behavioral problems and feelings of girls that they are different from peers.”
Another big problem is clear: parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
“They’re worried about the risk of pregnancy or even how they’re dealing with hygiene issues,” Kaplovitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls one woman whose daughter started menstruating at the age of 10.
Although there were signs and we talked about menstruation, it was not emotionally ready.
She came home from school scared and upset that she was the first of her friends.
There are many advertised theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no consistent evidence that the hormones in milk or other food products, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
In boys - as in girls - sexual maturation occurs earlier.
Kaplovitz claims that the prerequisite that has the most weight is an obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study of girls between the ages of 6 and 9, which linked the amount of fat in the body to periods of puberty.
Other data confirm this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Latin American girls tend to reach sexual maturity earlier than their white peers.
There are different explanations.
All over the world, early sexual maturity seems to be affected by everything from economic conditions and climate to genes.
Another mystery: although hair on the face and forehead of boys appears at a younger age, the tendency to complete early sexual maturation is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference confirmed the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and scalp hair occurs even in infants and children of childbearing age.
“We need to be careful about how we determine the true onset of sexual maturity,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Gorieb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not be shy to receive instructions from a pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This may mean an earlier than expected conversation,” Kaplovitz explained.
If you keep calm, your child will usually respond well.
Girls who blossom early need confirmation that even when this happens earlier than the one placed, this process is a normal part of life.
