Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could deprive the process of smoking cigarettes of pleasure.
One dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine dependence for a lifetime.
Further tests are needed before human trials begin, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of the Welle Cornell Medical College in New York said the first results are hopeful.
“We very much hope that such a vaccine strategy can finally help millions of smokers who have tried to quit by testing all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their nicotine dependence is strong enough to overcome these proxies.”
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that was designed to carry genetic information for the production of anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a stable flow of antibodies.
Antibodies track any nicotine molecules in the blood, neutralizing them before they reach the brain, preventing a smoker from getting a nicotine impact.
In the tests, vaccinated mice, who were subsequently given nicotine, continued their normal activities.
And mice who weren’t given the vaccine “relaxed,” and this is a sign that nicotine reached their brains, the researchers say.
These experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines have failed because they contained antibodies to the vaccines.
In order to maintain high levels of antibodies, injections had to be done so often that they proved expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibodies factories.
Professor Crystal said that if the future human vaccine was completely safe, it could be given to children before they have a desire to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine dependence.
But it is more likely that it will be used by smokers to quit smoking.
“They’ll know that if they start smoking again, they won’t get pleasure from that because of the nicotine vaccine, and that could help them get rid of this habit,” he said.
