We are frankly tired of feeling “working in school” when it comes to this issue.
But Internet connectivity for surfing, emailing, texting or downloading data will still be banned at a height of less than 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will be asked to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to aircraft mode.
Thus, there was still no “Words with Friends” – an intellectual online game in which actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when there was a disturbing incident: the actor was taken off the plane when he was on a flight with American Airlines for refusing to turn off the shutdown.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, will still need to be placed in the luggage compartment, as they can hurt someone if they fly all over the salon.
Calls from a mobile phone on the flight will also continue to be banned.
The regulatory powers over telephone calls belong to the Federal Communications Commission, not the FAU.
The FAU may remove the ban on some electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Council, a national transport safety expert at CBS News, said cell phones are still considered a risk.
“Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially create interference for navigation devices, but we know thanks to the FCC that they can create interference for cell towers when the plane is in the air,” Rosenker said.
The industry advisory committee set up by the FAU to study the issue recommended last month that the government allow the wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, there has been an increase in pressure on FAUs to mitigate restrictions on their use.
Critics, such as Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill, argue that there are no compelling security-related reasons for the ban.
Compliance with restrictions is also becoming increasingly difficult to ensure, as the use of devices has become widespread.
Some studies show that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore instructions to turn off their devices.
The FAU began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to reports of disruptions to navigation and communication equipment, when passengers began to carry FM radio receivers — high-tech gadgets of the time.
The new airliners are much more reliant on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also being developed and approved by the FAU as resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi at cruise altitude for several years now.
Planes modified for the Wi-Fi system are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of liners have been adapted for a wider use of electronic devices according to the new guidelines, Wart said.
Today’s electronic devices typically radiate radio signals of much lower power than the previous generations of devices.
Devices for reading e-books, for example, emit only minimal signals when scrolling pages.
But the signals become more powerful when the devices load or send the data.
Among those who sought to ease restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers was Amazon.com.
In 2011, representatives of the company loaded an entire airliner with their devices for reading Kindle e-books and flew on it to check for problems, but never detected them.
The members of the FAU Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about whether the use of the devices posed any risk.
Douglas Kidd, of the National Air Passenger Association, said in a statement that he considered interference from the devices to be real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other members of the committee said that there are only separate reports from pilots confirming that the devices can create interferences for aviation systems, and most of these reports are very old.
However, the Committee recommended that the FAU allow pilots to require passengers to disable the devices while landing on the devices in conditions of limited visibility.
A group of representatives of the tourism industry welcomed these changes, calling them a thoughtful step towards meeting passengers who are now using a wide range of technological devices.
“We are pleased that the FAU recognizes that passenger comfort is not incompatible with safety and protection,” said Roger Doe, director-general of the U.S. Tourism Association.
