Scientists have shed some light on how a dog’s tail movements are related to her mood.
Earlier studies have shown that happy dogs tilt their tail to the right (from the dog's point of view), while anxious dogs tilt their tail to the left.
But now scientists say that other representatives of the family of dogs can notice these subtle differences in the tail swing and react to them.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigar, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, says: “It is well known that people have different left and right sides of the brain that are involved in the formation of stimulants that cause positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to look at this and other species.
He added that just like humans, dogs’ right brains control the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To find out more about how dogs react to the various pulls of other dogs’ tails, the researchers watched the animals when they watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It’s likely that we’ll soon understand why their tails sometimes turn in one direction and sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigar said: “We showed dogs videos with dogs — either naturalistic versions, or silhouettes to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the tail movement and direct the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw that in the rest the dog was not expressing anything moved his tail to the right (from the dog’s point of view), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail was leaning mostly to the left (again from the dog’s point of view), their heartbeat increased and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigar said he didn’t think the dogs intentionally communicated with each other using these movements.
In fact, he believes that dogs have learned from their experience, which movements they should worry about, and which ones they do not.
He observes: “If there are several encounters with other dogs and often throwing their tail to one side is associated with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, then the dog will react based on that experience.”
Researchers say these results can give owners, veterinarians, and trainers a deeper understanding of their pet’s emotions.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a guest researcher at the University of Bristol’s Veterinary School, said it wasn’t the first study to check whether the left and right sides of dogs matter.
Last year, a team of scientists at Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left if they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right if they look at a happy dog.
In another scientific paper from the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported: “Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when their tail was tilted to the left rather than to the right, rather than becoming anxious,” researching the opposite behavior toward Italians.
He said the differences could be due to the fact that dogs in different studies did not fully perceive animals in movies or robot dogs as dogs.
It could be a useful study of how dogs react to real dogs, he explained.
“While there is enough evidence for different mammals that two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified, and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, it is likely that we will soon understand why their tails are sometimes directed in one direction and sometimes in the other.
