I don't know if I should have expected that.
Did I have to understand at the age of 18 that the leadership could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it?
It is obvious that the work in the election is not a predictable program of action, since our social dialogue will be formed by an opposition political party and by random events such as the Newtown massacre.
However, from all the examples I have listed above, it can be seen that they were largely the administration's own choice.
And that's what's bothering me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney represented an incomprehensible and crude alternative, it seemed that he was unable to make decisions on his own policies or views.
I thought that in his second term, Obama, freeing himself from the pressure of future elections, justified the hopes of which we have heard for such a long time.
However, when Obama’s rating fell below 45 percent this week, it became much harder to get back to 2008 through this book.
