Mohammad Mursi promised a "new Egypt" when he took an oath to become the country's first freely elected president, replacing Hosni Mubarak, who was overthrown 16 months ago.
At his inauguration before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Mursi also became the first freely elected Islamist president of the Arab world and the fifth head of state in Egypt after the overthrow of the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He took an oath before 18 judges in black robes in the courthouse on the bank of the Nile, built in the style of an ancient Egyptian temple.
“We are striving for a better future, for a new Egypt and a second republic,” Mursi said during a ceremony shown live on state television.
“Today, the Egyptian people laid the foundations of a new life – absolute freedom, genuine democracy and stability,” said Mursi, a 60-year-old engineer with an American background from the Muslim Brotherhood, a member of the Muslim Brotherhood, a friend of the Muslim Brotherhood, a member of a fundamentalist group that is the majority of its 84-year-old life.
