Only a few hundred supporters gathered at the courthouse to welcome the new president, and, unlike Mubarak’s presidential pump, the movement was stopped only for a short time to miss his native carousel along the normally bustling road connecting the city center.
Although Mursi was ridiculed as a non-charismatic “back-up wheel” of the Brothers, his personal prestige has grown sharply since his victory and a Friday speech in which he tried to present himself as a candidate not only against the 2011 autocracy of Islamists, but also all those who want to bring the child to an end.
“Today, Egypt is a civil, national, constitutional and modern state,” Mursi, dressed in a blue business suit with a red collar, told judges in the wooden paneled hall where he took the oath.
Mursi later went to Cairo University, where he was to give his inaugural speech.
He was given an official reception with an army orchestra, performing a national anthem, during which he stood on the stand "peacefully".
