A trip through the mud, rivers and jungles to provide free medical care
Dr. George Bwelle provides free medical care in the rural areas of Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend receiving hundreds of patients
In this West African country, there are not so many doctors — only one in 5,000 people.
Vote here or through your mobile device.
Dr. George Bwelle is one of the top 10 protagonists of CNN in 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other 10 protagonists to make him the CNN Hero of the Year.
This man will receive $250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, George Bwelle saw his father come back to life and fall into a state of unconsciousness again, wandering through hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
James Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but the infection spread to the brain and caused hematoma, which resembled himself for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said George Bwelle.
If we had the money, we'd get him out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwelle accompanied his father for years to overcrowded clinics and hospitals, receiving any treatment they could get.
“It’s not easy,” Bwelle said.
“You can leave home at 5 a.m., go to the hospital to be the first, but you’re not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people may die because of what they have to wait for.
The situation hasn't changed much since Bwelle's father died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor per 5,000 people in Cameroon.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 people.
And even if the Cameroonians could go to the doctor, many of them would not have it in their pockets.
Two out of five people in the country live on the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of healthcare expenditures in the country are private.
“Their only problem is poverty,” Bwelle said.
“Because of poverty, they can’t enjoy their lives.”
Seeing the suffering of his father and many of his compatriots, Bwelle was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. George Bwelle and his team of volunteers conducted 700 free surgeries.
He himself became a doctor and works as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
He also founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes weekend trips to rural areas to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have assisted nearly 32,000 people.
Nearly every Friday, he and up to 30 other people are loaded into vans, tied to the roofs of medical supplies and going across the intersection to visit the village in need.
They are not always accompanied by luck.
Many times they had to push cars through rivers and dirt.
But when they arrive, they meet them as real heroes: it’s a holiday with songs and dances and the best venues that the locals have to offer.
Free medical care in these villages is really the reason for the holiday, and Bwelle with its wide smile and unlimited energy more than happily join the fun.
The next morning, the brigade begins to receive hundreds of patients.
“We accept 500 people on each trip,” Bwelle said.
They come from all over the district within a radius of 60 kilometers from the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides a variety of medical services.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may get crisps, donated glasses, or free birth certificates—documents needed for school that many poor families simply can’t afford.
In the evening, the brigade performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
Surgery is usually performed in a school building, a municipality, or at home; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the postoperative area to free up space for the next person.
Using a generator to illuminate the operational and sanitary treatment equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
This is an unrelenting pace, but the brigade’s determination is usually helped to support the village musicians.
“They’re hitting the drums all night so we wake up and keep working,” Bwelle said.
On Sunday, members of the brigade are sent back to the city, tired but proud of their work.
This group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students, conducted 700 free surgeries over the past year, and they know that their help can be of great importance to those they help.
One person explained that the free operation he received to treat hernia will allow him to work again.
“It will change the future for me and my family,” the man said.
In addition to these clinical practices on weekends and hospital work, surgeon Bwelle also works at night in private medical clinics around Yaoundé.
It is this second job, he said, that provides 60 per cent of the financing of his non-profit organization; the rest is covered by private donations.
“I don’t even know when he’s sleeping,” said Katie O’Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia, who volunteers with the Bwelle group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to make money for the organization so that he can continue these campaigns.
For future doctors and nurses, such as O’Malley, who come from the U.S. and Europe to join Bwelle in realizing his tasks, this is an opportunity for practice that they would never get at home.
“We were given the opportunity to assist with surgeries where we helped remove blood stains or hold tools for Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley said.
As a second-year student, you would never get such an opportunity in America.
Voluntary students usually pay for their own trip to Cameroon, often arriving with donated medications.
But upon arrival in Yaoundé, their food, transport and training pays Bwelle.
“He’s a hero, no doubt,” O’Malley said.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon endlessly.
For Bwelle, the almost constant workload is not a difficult test.
Helping others live a happy life, fulfilling their father’s promise is something that brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bwelle said.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do this to make people laugh to reduce their pain.
Go to the ASCOVIME website and see what you can help.
