The general director of the agency is Larissa Afonina, the editor-in-chief - Nikolai Ulyanov.
Recently, Rosbalt did not appear in the ratings of the federal media – neither by citation nor by audience.
In October, the agency took the 25th place in the ranking of visits of Russian media sites according to the version of LiveInternet.
According to LiveInternet, the average daily audience of the site rosbalt.ru is about 150,000 unique visitors (and up to 500,000 views), monthly - about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials in the last five months - remarks about the helplessness of the Kremlin in relations with Ukraine, the death of the soloist of the group "King and the Joke", pogroms in the capital Biryuleve.
The conflict between Rosbalta and Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when an amendment to the media law that banned journalists from using uncensored weapons came into force.
The agency found a banned vocabulary in two videos published on the agency’s website (“Jigit of Krasnodar” and “Pussy Riot polluted the oil turrets”).
The following pages describe it in a different way.
Roskomnadzor on the basis of the detected video materials accused Rosbalt of gross and systematic violation of the media law and appealed to the court with a demand to withdraw the license from the agency.
In "Rosbalt" stated that the claims of the agency are wrong: first, the videos were not editorial materials, secondly, the parent words in them were masked, and, thirdly, immediately after the warning the video was removed from the site.
Representatives of the agency appealed Roskomnadzor’s claims in the world court – and when on October 22, 2013, Mosgorsud accepted Roskomnadzor’s lawsuit, the examination of these complaints was still ongoing.
However, on the 25th, the world judge decided not in favor of "Rosbalt": the editor-in-chief Nikolai Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the Code on Administrative Offences and fined 20 thousand rubles - 10 thousand for each roll.
Obviously, this predetermined the outcome of the hearing in Mosgorsud - if we give up the idea that the outcome could have been predetermined even earlier.
On October 31, the court decided to declare the certificate of registration of “Rosbalt” invalid, effectively depriving the agency of the status of the media.
It cannot be said that “Rosbalt” during this confrontation remained alone.
The agency was supported by the deputies of the State Duma (the statement in the name of the head of Roskomnadzor Alexander Zharov on October 10 was signed by 26 deputies; the document itself was submitted on the initiative of the CPRF).
The head of the Union of Journalists of Russia Vsevolod Bogdanov, the chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists Pavel Gusev and the head of the Presidential Council on Human Rights Mikhail Fedotov declared the illegal closure of the publication.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, the management of Roskomnadzor even gave him some guarantees that the case will not come until the license is revoked.
The court over "Rosbalt" showed: under whose jurisdiction it is safer to be the media in Russia today - a big question.
Syria Destroyed Chemical Weapons Equipment
Syria has destroyed all claimed chemical weapons production facilities, the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons acknowledged.
This first phase of disarmament was completed one day before the deadline set by Damascus.
By November 1, Syria had to destroy production facilities and other auxiliary facilities designed to prepare combat toxins for use, according to the BBC.
The destruction of the stockpiles of toxic substances or their chemical components should be completed by mid-2014.
According to the representative of the OPCW, the toxic substances are currently in sealed warehouses.
International inspectors went to Syria after more than 1,400 people were killed in a chemical attack on the outskirts of Damascus on August 21.
The main task of the inspectors was not to waste time – to prevent the Syrian authorities from producing more chemical weapons – and to destroy the infrastructure for mixing chemicals and ammunition.
These production capacities will now be closely monitored to prevent them from being repaired.
The next milestone is mid-November: By this time, the OPCW and the Syrians must agree on a detailed plan to destroy existing stockpiles of toxic substances.
There's a lot of questions here.
Where will they be destroyed?
Who will provide the equipment for this?
All Syrian statements will be carefully checked by the Western intelligence services.
They will be prepared to advise inspectors of new facilities for inspection if there are grounds to suspect that Damascus has not been fully disclosed.
The United States believes that the bombing was carried out by regular troops.
Syria and Russia insist that this is a matter of the hands of the Syrian rebels.
The world community has demanded from the Syrian leadership, in accordance with the agreement reached through Russia, to destroy or bring into disrepair all capacity for the production of ammunition, poisoning gases and liquids and for the filling of ammunition.
Now that this phase has passed, the next step should be the destruction of the chemical weapons already in the Syrian army.
It is estimated that there may be more than 1,000 tons of neuro-paralytic toxins, skin-repellent mustard gas and other prohibited chemicals stored in several dozen different locations.
To destroy it, it is necessary for the OSCE and the Syrian authorities to agree on a timetable of action to begin with, which takes two weeks.
OPCW Field Operations Chief Jerry Smith told the BBC that his inspectors had “personally monitored the destruction of the equipment.”
“They are no longer able to carry out further production or mixing of chemical weapons,” he said.
The OPCW said inspectors visited 21 of the 23 sites in Syria and made sure that the factories for the production of ammunition and toxins were either destroyed or invalidated.
The remaining two facilities are too dangerous to carry out an inspection there, the document says, but the equipment from there was transported and checked by OPCW specialists.
According to Smith, the process of destroying the chemical weapons infrastructure was “particularly difficult” as it had to work in the face of ongoing conflict.
In early October, the OPCW received the Nobel Peace Prize, but, according to Smith, the inspectors did not yet have time to celebrate it – they were too busy with work.
John Kerry says in his unprecedented admission that U.S. espionage "has gone awry far"
John Kerry has demonstrated a softening of the tactics of protecting U.S. surveillance programs, making an unprecedented admission that in some cases U.S. espionage “has gone awry far.”
The secretary of state also admitted that he was guilty, along with Barack Obama, of being “on autopilot” at the time of Edward Snowden’s loud revelations about the NSA’s espionage activities.
These leaks put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic scandal with its allies.
Speaking on video at an open government conference in London, Mr. Kerry said: “There is no doubt that the president and I, as well as other members of the government, have actually perceived some of the things that are happening on autopilot.”
He then became the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had gone too far, but stressed that nobody’s rights had been violated.
He said: “In some cases, it has gone awry far.
And the president is determined to shed light on the issue and explain himself to the people, and is now conducting a thorough analysis so that no one has a feeling of abuse.
I assure you, there is no abuse of innocent people in this process.”
Mr. Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA acted on good grounds and that his surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: “We are working in a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up.
There is radical extremism in the world, reckless and determined to kill people, explode people and attack governments.
And if you were able to intercept it, stop it before it happens?
“We actually prevented plane crashes, building explosions, and killing people because we were able to find out about these plans in advance.”
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will go to Europe to help resolve issues related to alleged U.S. espionage abroad and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint anti-terrorism measures with the U.S., the chairman of the Senate subcommittee on Europe said.
Connecticut Senator Chris Murphy said he had spoken to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti-terrorist organizations over the disappointment with the National Security Agency's monitoring.
“For the national security interests of the United States, it is really important that Europeans remain our supporters in our common counter-terrorism efforts,” said Murphy, a first-time Democrat who chairs the Senate’s subcommittee on international affairs and European affairs.
“And I am going to Europe to let them know that we must continue to cooperate in the fight against terrorism, despite their anger over these NSA programs.”
The news that the NSA has collected millions of phone records in Europe has worsened relations with some of the U.S. allies, although the head of the agency said this week that they were inaccurate and reflected the misunderstanding of the metadata that the U.S. gathered by NATO and Co.
Other revelations have included documents released by Snowden, which indicate that the NSA monitored the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel, as well as the phones of approximately 34 other world leaders.
National Intelligence Director James Clapper defended espionage against the Allies as necessary and said it was a common practice on both sides.
Against the background of this noise, Murphy said his office is organizing a congressional trip, which is expected to take place this year, and that he hopes that members of both parties and both chambers will join the delegation.
The names of the other participating legislators should be announced in the coming days.
According to him, the program of the trip is still in the development stage.
Although Murphy said the purpose of the trip was to help improve relationships, he said that some degree of “hardness from the best incentives” would also be manifested.
He said European leaders should be honest with their people about what spying programs they have used for many years.
“While we can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, they must also agree that we are not the only ones engaged in intelligence activities,” Murphy said.
Meanwhile, Mr. Kerry should head to the Middle East and Poland this weekend to address the issues of hostility towards the US strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as U.S. intelligence.
